         <abstract>
            <p>Using in-substance defeasance as a debt extinguishment method has been criticized in prior literature because of the wealth transfer, from the stockholders to the debt holders, inherent in the transaction. This paper illustrates that stockholders may prefer an in-substance defeasance to an outright purchase of discounted debt after considering the tax consequences of both debt extinguishment methods. A model of the cash flows associated with a debt purchase and debt defeasance is developed, and the sensitivity of the two methods to changes in the maturity length of the retired debt, the corporation's cost of debt, and the riskiness of the extinguished debt relative to U.S. Government securities is examined.</p>
         </abstract>
